entries.Description:
In celebration of National Day, #DoingGood campaign, NParks is organising an Invasive Species Management activity at Telok Blangah Hill Park to encourage the community to come together and care for our environment.

Invasive species pose a threat to biodiversity. They compete for space, light, water and nutrients with other native species. You can often find them smothering our native trees in the park. By removing these invasive species, you are protecting the natural ecosystem and creating a better home for our local flora and fauna.

 

Come and have a hands-on session to learn what are the invasive climbers that are not welcomed in our forest.

BBBS is a regular series of Saturdates (playdates held on Saturdays) where children with special needs will be invited to participate in fun-filled activities planned by the team. BBBS 5.0 focuses on inclusive volunteering, and we aim to provide a common space for children and youths of varying abilities to intermingle and socialise.

Unlike previous runs of BBBS, where youth volunteers will plan for playdates, the playdates for BBBS 5.0 will be planned and organised by youths with special needs (YSNs). We would like to invite you to join us as a volunteer mentor to the YSNs, where you will guide and work alongside YSNs in ideating, curating and facilitating the playdates for children with special needs.

The Saturdates are stipulated to take place in October 2022 and planning with YSNs will begin in August 2022. The commitment period is as follows: 

  1. Mandatory Orientation & Training (29 July 2022, 7.30 to 9.30pm)
  2. Sessions with YSNs to ideate and plan for playdates (5 Saturdays between early August to mid September 2022; half day)
  3. 1 playdate (Saturday, between late September to mid October 2022; half day)

Prior to the above, we will be inviting you to an online chit-chat cum sharing session on 13 July 2022 (Wednesday), from 8 to 9pm. An email consisting of the Zoom details will be sent to you if you have successfully registered for the session. 

We look forward to seeing you and sharing more insights about BBBS 5.0!

This opportunity is a youth-led initiative part of Youth Corps Leaders Programme. 

I Choose Hope aims to help Study Buddies (Primary 1 - Secondary 2 students under the Study Buddy programme at CampusImpact) to choose hope - to improve their mental wellness by encouraging them to reframe their mindsets. This will be done through creating an art journal that meets their needs. The content of this journal will be created by us, while the illustrations in the art journal will be done by the children. We are looking for a graphic designer who can design the journal and bring out the best in the children's drawings.

entries.Name: Beach clean-up @ Coney Island Park
entries.Description:
In celebration of National Day, #DoingGood campaign, NParks is organising a  Beach Clean-Up at Coney Island Park to encourage the community to come together and care for our environment.

 

Trash and debris such a plastic can be found on the beach along Coney Island Park are regularly being washed ashore. entries.Description:
In celebration of National Day, #DoingGood campaign, NParks is organising an Invasive Species Management activity at Coney Island Park to encourage the community to come together and care for our environment.

Invasive species pose a threat to biodiversity. They compete for space, light, water and nutrients with other native species. By removing these invasive species, you are protecting the natural ecosystem and creating a better home for our local flora and fauna.

 

Come down to Coney Island Park on the 3 Aug 2022 at 0900hrs and make a difference to the environment!

entries.Name: Mangrove clean-up @ Pasir Ris Park
entries.Description:
In celebration of National Day, #DoingGood campaign, NParks is organising a mangrove clean up at Pasir Ris Park Mangroves to encourage the community to come together and care for our environment.

 

Mangroves are a source of food and a nursery ground for our biodiversity and they also physically protect coastlines by breaking the sea waves during storm surges. During high tide, man-made waste such as plastics and foam pieces get trapped in our mangrove forest.

 

Come down to Pasir Ris Park on the 16th July at 0800hrs and you can help to clean up this fragile ecosystem so that the amazing mangrove flora and fauna can thrive for their conservation and our enjoyment.

entries.Name: Turtle Nesting Patrol [Y-Y]
entries.Description:
It's the Turtle Nesting Season right now from now (July) till September! Join us in our efforts to patrol the beaches of Sentosa at dawn/dusk on the following days to look out for nesting turtle treks and possible nest locations to support conservation efforts in partnership with Sentosa Development Corporation. 

Please note that the chances of seeing a turtle is low as they usually nest in the wee hours into the night, so please set your expectations right before committing to this volunteering opportunity.

The Youth Corps Singapore Sustainability Cluster will be running a Turtle Nesting Patrol Training (either Physical or Virtual) and you MUST be trained before volunteering.

To apply for this opportunity, you need to commit to 1 training session and at least 2 patrol sessions.

-

This event is organised by Youth Corps Singapore Sustainability Cluster in collaboration with Sentosa Development Corporation.

Neighbour Cares is back for a new year and we would like to invite YOU to embark on this journey with us!

27 July, 2000-2200: Virtual Welcome Tea Session on Zoom

entries.Name: [SSO@BL/TJ] We are looking for ComLink Befrienders!
entries.NameTooltip: [SSO@BL/TJ] We are looking for ComLink Befrienders!
entries.Description:
We are looking for ComLink Befrienders!

 

Low-income individuals and families often face multiple stressors and may not know what help is available. Even if they do, they often have to repeat their circumstances and visit different agencies to apply for various schemes, which can be taxing on the families. They may also often be preoccupied with bread-and-butter issues and may not have the bandwidth to consider future or long-term goals, which affects their ability to seize the opportunities to build a better life.

These families will benefit from close action planning and befriending support – someone they can turn to for advice/help, as well as to hold them accountable to their goals and ensure they are making progress over time. However, not all families have issues that may require professional intervention. ComLink Befriending was set up to help bridge this gap and make it easier for families to access help in a more coordinated, convenient and comprehensive way.

As an ComLink Befriender, you will befriend and journey with the family, while working hand-in-hand with an SSO Coordinator who will work backend with both government agencies and community partners. Together, an integrated "support and action plan" for the family will be developed. In essence, the ComLink Befriender will:

  • Be paired up with another befriender and work with an SSO Coordinator in supporting two low-income families towards achieving their goals;
  • Journey with the family, nudge and encourage them towards these goals, and update the SSO Coordinator on the family' progress; and 
  • Provide feedback and suggestions to improve the operating model, in preparation for a scale-up.

entries.Name: Community Volunteer Programme
entries.Description:
The main role of a Community Volunteer is to educate and engage environmental offenders. The offences, which CVs can engage an offender on, include:

    • Littering in public places;
    • Pet defecation in public places;
    • Smoking in prohibited places;
    • Spitting in public places;
    • Urinating in public places and
    • Leaving the engine of a stationary vehicle running

Should CVs observe any smoky vehicles on the road, they could take down details of the vehicle, date, time of offence and submit to NEA for follow up action. All CVs will be required to adopt a ‘Bright Spot’ and are required to participate in at least one activity per month. Other than scheduled patrols, CVs could also conduct other activities within the adopted ‘Bright Spot’ such as educational outreach and litter-picking.

 

Training

Individuals who are keen to be a CV will require to attend a foundation training which is held on 2 consecutive Saturday mornings (9.00am-1.00pm) at Environment Building and pass a theory assessment. Upon completion of the foundation training, CVs will then be scheduled to attend 2 sessions of practical training subsequently to hone their engagement skills further. We will provide you with the practical training schedule upon completion of the foundation training. Only successful applicants who have passed the foundation training and practical training will be issued with an authority card with 3 years validity.

 

Criteria

Interested volunteers will have to fulfil the following criteria below in order to participate in the programme:

 

  • Minimum 18 years old and above
  • Singapore Citizen or Permanent Resident
  • Physically and mentally fit
  • No prior criminal record
  • No previous offence under NEA’s jurisdiction
  • Mature, responsible and committed
  • Passionate about keeping the environment clean & green
